                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Mercantile Library.<lb/></p>
            <p>Philad<hi rend="sup">a</hi> Jany. 14&#44; 1888.<lb/>
                Rev. S. Morais&#44; No. 546 N. 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St.<lb/> 
                My dear Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>I am under the neces&#45;<lb/>sity of brining up the Gordon matter<lb/> again in <hi rend="underline">The Record</hi> because I was<lb/> misled by the Canada paper&#44; and<lb/> charged Dr. Gordon with &#34;deplorable<lb/> and inexcusable carelessness&#59;&#34; and<lb/> now I have to explain.  But you<lb/> will see that I have not mentioned<lb/> Mr. Marcus.<lb/></p>
            <p>I think that you must be amused<lb/> by the stupid pertinacity of the men<lb/> with whom I deal.  They are resolved<lb/> not to learn&#44; if they can avoid it.<lb/>  It is only a third&#45;rate or fourth&#45;rate<lb/> class of men who keep up this &#34;two&#45;<lb/>kinds&#45;of&#45;wine&#34; effort.  Our scholars <hi rend="underline">all</hi><lb/> agree with me&#59; many thank me.  The<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>discussion rages at present in dis&#45;<lb/>tant regions&#45;&#45;in Canada and in the<lb/> South.<lb/></p>
            <p><hi rend="underline">The Voice</hi> &#40;Prohib. organ&#41; made<lb/> a definite assertion about ancient<lb/> Gr. and Lat. Chr. authors.  I offered<lb/> &#36;20&#45;&#45; to <hi rend="underline">any</hi> one who would send<lb/> to <hi rend="underline">The Record</hi> before Ch<hi rend="sup">mas</hi> <hi rend="underline">a single</hi><lb/> <hi rend="underline">sentence</hi> of the kind.  Not a line<lb/> sent&#44; and the &#34;<hi rend="underline">Voice</hi>&#34; has never al&#45;<lb/>luded to the offer&#44; although it<lb/> was sent to the Ed<hi rend="sup">r</hi>. with my name<lb/> and address&#33;  Such is Prohibition<lb/> candor&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>I have never been able to sat&#45;<lb/>isfy myself <hi rend="underline">perfectly</hi> in regard to<lb/> the thought which a Hebrew had<lb/> in his mind when he used the<lb/> word &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  It appears to me that<lb/> if some scholar would furnish for<lb/> one of the Quarterlies a thorough and<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>complete and conclusive exposition&#45;&#45;<lb/> covering the post&#45;Biblical Heb. books<lb/> and taking in cognate languages&#44;<lb/> he would render a valuable service<lb/> to the learned world&#44; I have made<lb/> this suggestion to several of<lb/> our Professors&#44; but I do not know<lb/> that any one will undertake the<lb/> work.  Hosea iv&#58; 11 is a puzzle.<lb/>  And if the word stands for <hi rend="underline">new</hi><lb/> <hi rend="underline">wine</hi> in various stages of the prepara&#45;<lb/>tion&#44; why did not Isaac ask for<lb/> plenty of the completed article&#63;  Why<lb/> ask for <hi rend="underline">new wine</hi>&#63;  For&#44; wine which<lb/> is completely prepared is as much<lb/> a product of the earth as that which<lb/> is one&#45;half or three&#45;fourths completed.<lb/>  We might ask for plenty of <hi rend="underline">wool</hi>&#44;<lb/> but would not be likely to ask for<lb/> plenty of <hi rend="underline">yarn</hi>.  We should go on<lb/> and ask for plenty of <hi rend="underline">cloth</hi>.<lb/></p>
            <p>But I will not dwell further&#44; I am<lb/> Yours respectfully&#44; S. C. Brace.<lb/></p>
            </body>
